commit.message:
Update README /w stackforge info & reword doc-link

Send users to stackforge and reword the doc-link.
Addressed all last comments in patchset 20

Merge branch 'master' of github.com:dotcloud/openstack-docker

Conflicts:
	nova-driver/driver.py
Various changes following Nova review on gerrit
Implemented snapshots and fix some tests

Merge pull request #11 from bcwaldon/client-testing

Testing of DockerHTTPClient & other small refactoring

Drop configurable stop_container timeout

Nobody was using it, anyways.
Move is_daemon_running from client to driver
Move get_registry_port from client to driver

Merge pull request #7 from paulczar/master

setup script to work on openstack installed by rcbops chef recipes

Merge pull request #10 from bcwaldon/fix-tests

Correct fake client/driver initialization & small nit-picky fixes

Fix instantiation of a fake DockerDriver

* Move mock client to nova.tests.virt.docker.mock_client
* Allow overriding of the client class in DockerDriver.__init__
* Mock out the one DockerDriver method that depended on 'fake'
* Remove DockerDriver.fake attribute

issue_comments.body: Ok, that simple "sleep" works. I'll add a comment on top of the line you added though to find something more reliable (like watching the "tasks" file with a total timeout).

Allow me to apologize for the dumb question, but: is docker running?

If it is—which version are you using? (Maybe you're using an old version, which doesn't have support for the REST API used by the Nova driver?)

Thank you!

Docker is actually not running, does not show up in `ps aux | grep docker`. I pulled the latest Devstack and Docker from git around an hour back. Do I need to install Docker separately? The installation doc does not say so!

That's a very good point, we'll have to review those docs. Very sorry about that.

Meanwhile, all you have to do should be:

```
curl get.docker.io | sh
```

(Assuming that you're running a Debian or Ubuntu system; if you are running another distro, chances are that you will be missing AUFS support!)
On a closer look I realized that I do need to install docker separately. Thanks for the pointer. I am closing this issue now.
Yes, the driver needs Docker daemon to run on the side to function properly. That's the wanted behavior, but it's true that we should specify in the doc, I'll fix that. Thanks for testing!
I thought it might be useful to add a check in the installation script. I sent a pull request, feel free to merge or reject.

Could you copy paste the output of the setup_on_devstack.sh?

Also, could you confirm that you have a fresh version of devstack installed in /opt/stack?

Thanks
